59
00:06:42,050 --> 00:06:51,720
Finally, our clients are removed from the handcuffs and it's explained to them, allegedly, that this is policy, this is procedure, right?

60
00:06:52,761 --> 00:07:02,192
There's a brief information given about something related to an anonymous tip, and maybe the vehicle being related to that tip, and eventually my clients are asked,

61
00:07:03,360 --> 00:07:05,201
do you think your friend is paying a joke on you?

62
00:07:05,221 --> 00:07:17,588
And again, my clients who are, to be quite honest, who are traumatized by this, who are still traumatized to this day, and for people who don't know it, when we're talking about last summer, what we're talking about is not just the wake of George Floyd.

63
00:07:18,048 --> 00:07:23,271
At the time that my clients were stopped, we're talking about just about the three-month window after

64
00:07:24,071 --> 00:07:31,878
the trial of the murder of George Floyd, which if many people remember happened, the verdict came down on the exact same day that another black man was shot and killed.

65
00:07:32,238 --> 00:07:42,207
And shortly in that same week I believe the young boy the Latino boy in New York had been shot in the back of the head so I mean, we're talking about the timing of this incident.

66
00:07:42,908 --> 00:07:55,838
despite how any department may call this something that was innocent, was happening in a highly, highly polarized and highly traumatic time for people of color, at least anybody, to be frank, who's watching the news right now.

67
00:07:57,259 --> 00:08:07,727
What I like to tell people is that it's very hard to believe as a person of color that officer friendly exists anymore in America, because that is not the lived experience of most people of color when they engage with police.

68
00:08:08,808 --> 00:08:12,631
So ultimately, as my clients did nothing wrong, they're, they're like, go.

69
00:08:13,612 --> 00:08:15,835
And unfortunately, that's not the end of the story.

70
00:08:16,175 --> 00:08:28,187
What follows is then quite a bit of difficulty in terms of gathering any additional information, trying to get documentation of this experience, trying to understand why it happened and what they can do in response to it.

71
00:08:28,587 --> 00:08:46,319
And as they sort of struggle to try to do that on their own, they're eventually referred to lawyers for civil rights where I work and so then we with the assistance of a pro bono firm started to sit down with them and put the pieces together and gather documents and information to produce what you guys have now seen which is this complaint that was

72
00:08:47,479 --> 00:08:55,282
late last month to support them and to ensure that there's some transparency and some accountability around what my clients experienced.

73
00:08:55,562 --> 00:09:03,664
And then to think about what can the, what can the sort of referration material, like steps be, what can we do to ensure that this doesn't happen to other people?

74
00:09:06,425 --> 00:09:08,726
And we are curious to hear more about that.

75
00:09:08,746 --> 00:09:14,148
I wonder if you could also summarize what is being asked for from your clients, from the city.

76
00:09:15,295 --> 00:09:20,398
Sure, so I mean, I would categorize it in basically in two ways.

77
00:09:20,758 --> 00:09:22,820
So there's some dignity asked here, right?

78
00:09:23,060 --> 00:09:24,381
They're looking for an apology.

79
00:09:24,681 --> 00:09:30,624
At the end of the day, they're looking to be told or acknowledged that their experience was wrong, right?

80
00:09:30,684 --> 00:09:36,508
And as simplistic as that seems, you'd find it, it's a very rare thing, unfortunately, for people to receive that.

81
00:09:37,168 --> 00:09:43,953
So that's sort of front and foremost for them is that desire to just be treated like a dignified individual.

82
00:09:45,615 --> 00:09:54,337
Then they have multiple asks that are related to reforming this process going forward, ensuring that there's structural changes so that other individuals don't have the experience they did.

83
00:09:54,877 --> 00:10:08,739
We're looking for some changes to the policies and procedures that are existing that simply did not go far enough to assist the clients, and then the creation of new policies and procedures to ensure that this sort of behavior doesn't continue going forward.

84
00:10:09,159 --> 00:10:11,060
And we'd be looking for that to be done in

85
00:10:12,460 --> 00:10:15,202
in concert with an expert that we could recommend.

86
00:10:15,423 --> 00:10:25,811
So somebody who has the cultural competence to recognize sort of the racial lens that has to be used when thinking through the development of this practice, this practice or this policy or this procedure.

87
00:10:26,947 --> 00:10:48,156
Coupled with that, we're also looking for ongoing mandatory implicit bias sort of training to ensure that, again, these officers have some awareness about the context of American history and present day in terms of stopping two young black people at gunpoint with, you know, a dozen cops or half a dozen cops.

88
00:10:49,236 --> 00:10:59,101
So thinking through ongoing training that isn't just one-off, you know, because we know that implicit bias training does not do anything unless it's repeated, unless it's mandatory.

89
00:10:59,501 --> 00:11:03,643
So not looking for voluntary training and not looking for one-off training, but something that's going to be repeated.

90
00:11:04,924 --> 00:11:09,666
And then we're looking for compensation for the clients themselves, for the emotional distress that they've experienced.

91
00:11:11,047 --> 00:11:11,307
