168
00:18:35,064 --> 00:18:45,077
I mean we have been reached out to by city council officials, you know, activists on the ground, just concerned folks, I've gotten to legal events and lawyers and walked up to me and been like,

169
00:18:46,123 --> 00:19:02,180
I live in Medford, tell me what I can do to help you know so I think there is really a desire on the ground there, and I think that is a really powerful thing and I think the police department should be really afraid of that, because at the end of the day, you guys are taxpayers, you guys make the decisions about the community that you pay for.

170
00:19:02,540 --> 00:19:07,806
And so if they have to respond to you, even in a way that they don't always have to respond to me, you know.

171
00:19:08,386 --> 00:19:12,649
And so I think continue to do what you're doing, you know, reaching out at city council meetings.

172
00:19:13,249 --> 00:19:14,910
There are people sending letters to the mayor.

173
00:19:16,071 --> 00:19:32,101
I understand that you guys recently had a diversity officer that was hired for Medford, and that she's not been there very long but I think really encouraging and pressuring her to do the good work to actually move the needle and ensuring that your city and town is giving her the resources and agency to do that good work.

174
00:19:32,562 --> 00:19:33,883
I think that is really important.

175
00:19:34,603 --> 00:19:53,888
It may not be a role yet that you guys can see dividends paying from, but the fact that you have that role is such a powerful thing because there's so many cities and towns that don't even have it yet, you know, and so I think there are a lot of pieces on the ground that you like tools you guys have to work with to try to get this message moving forward, but more so than anything you just can't allow complacency.

